      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>New Jersey environmentalists, backed by Rutgers University professors and other experts in climate patterns, urged the Clinton Administration yesterday to lead the world in reducing greenhouse gases to fight global warming.</p>
        <p>''If we have the technologies to do this, or can come up with the technologies to do this, why wait?'' said Dave Robinson, state climatologist and director of the Rutgers research program on climate change.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>New Jersey environmentalists, backed by Rutgers University professors and other experts in climate patterns, urged the Clinton Administration yesterday to lead the world in reducing greenhouse gases to fight global warming.</p>
        <p>''If we have the technologies to do this, or can come up with the technologies to do this, why wait?'' said Dave Robinson, state climatologist and director of the Rutgers research program on climate change.</p>
        <p>Mr. Robinson said New Jersey's average winter temperatures have not changed in 100 years. But summer temperatures, on average, appear to be one-half degree Fahrenheit higher than in 1900. He attributed that to warmer summers since 1980.</p>
        <p>NEW JERSEY DAILY BRIEFING</p>
      </block>
